{"source_key":"sha256-c6e31965606144ec3d8cd5675dba0301","record_index":261,"record_hash":"sha256:bc35a86e8be48259d8dcf76d4ac67b7eb7065b48fe36a5cbe5d41be711f015e6","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:22:51.272Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n[P1] Environment capture is happening inside the GitMeta writer.  \\n[gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:169) calls `capture_environment(repo_path)` from `write_transcript_batch`, which makes the persistence layer orchestrate repo observation. That blurs the intended boundary: `gitmeta` should persist already-decided session/turn data, not discover worktree/stacks/commits. It also forces `gitmeta` to know environment DTOs at [gitmeta.rs:12](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:12). Cleaner shape: capture orchestration asks GitMeta which records were accepted or passes a lazy snapshot hook, then GitMeta only writes the resulting `EnvironmentObservation`.\\n\\n[P1] Repository/context resolution is duplicated below the boundary.  \\nCLI already resolves the workdir at [cli.rs:148](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:148), then `gitmeta` opens GitMeta at [gitmeta.rs:100](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:100), and environment opens another repo at [environment.rs:117](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:117). That violates the repo instruction to not rediscover Git repositories inside business logic. `capture_environment` should take an already-open `&gix::Repository` or some narrow snapshot context from the capture layer.\\n\\n[P2] The local `EmptyRefMetadata` shim makes agentlog own workspace metadata semantics.  \\n[environment.rs:220](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:220) manually checks `virtual_branches.toml`, then [environment.rs:382](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:382) implements a fake `RefMetadata` stack just to make plain Git fit `head_info`. That’s a boundary smell: agentlog now knows too much about GitButler metadata plumbing. If plain Git needs empty metadata, that helper belongs near `but_workspace`/`but_core`, or `head_info` should expose a default path.\\n\\n[P2] `environment.rs` mixes snapshot collection, storage schema, and target projection.  \\nThe same module defines persisted JSON structs at [environment.rs:26](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:26), opens repos and reads workspace metadata at [environment.rs:117](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:117), and derives `observed_targets` at [environment.rs:243](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:243). This is maintainable for a POC, but it’s the main place the change feels generated-big. Smaller split: keep DTO/projection here, move repo snapshot acquisition behind one narrow function/type, or name the module `environment_snapshot` and make the “adapter” boundary explicit.\\n\\n[P3] No provider/transcript vocabulary leak found in environment capture.  \\nTranscript provider/model stay in transcript/GitMeta source metadata, and environment review `provider` at [environment.rs:76](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:76) is always `None` today. That field is a bit speculative, but it matches the review-target shape from the spec more than it leaks Codex/Claude concepts.\\n\\nBest simplification: move `capture_environment` out of `gitmeta::write_transcript_batch` first. That single change would clean up the biggest boundary issue without turning this into an architecture party.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:22:51.272Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}